# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: detroit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:detroit/1820-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The **second cholera pandemic** (1826–1837), also known as the **Asiatic cholera pandemic**, was a cholera pandemic that reached from India across Western Asia to Europe, Great Britain, and the Americas, as well as east to China and Japan.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Cholera caused more deaths than any other epidemic disease in the 19th century, and as such, researchers consider it a defining epidemic disease of the century.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The medical community now believes cholera to be exclusively a human disease, spread through many means of travel during the time, and transmitted through warm fecal-contaminated river waters and contaminated foods.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] During the second pandemic, the scientific community varied in its beliefs about the causes of cholera.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The first cholera pandemic (1817–24) began near Kolkata and spread throughout Southeast Asia to the Middle East, eastern Africa, and the Mediterranean coast.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] While cholera had spread across India many times previously, this outbreak went farther; it reached as far as China and the Mediterranean Sea before receding.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Hundreds of thousands of people died as a result of this pandemic, including many British soldiers from the presidency armies, which attracted European attention.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] This was the first of several cholera pandemics to sweep through Asia and Europe during the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] This first pandemic spread over an unprecedented range of territory, affecting many countries throughout Asia.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Historians believe that the first pandemic had lingered in Indonesia and the Philippines in 1830.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Although not much is known about the journey of the cholera pandemic in east India, many believe that this pandemic began, like the first, with outbreaks along the Ganges Delta in India.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] From there, the disease spread along trade routes to cover most of India.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] By 1828, the disease had traveled to China.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Cholera was also reported in China in 1826 and 1835, and in Japan in 1831.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In 1829, Iran was apparently infected with cholera from Afghanistan.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Cholera reached the southern tips of the Ural Mountains in 1829.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] On 26 August 1829, the first cholera case was recorded in Orenburg with reports of outbreaks in Bugulma (7 November), Buguruslan (5 December), Menzelinsk (2 January 1830), and Belebey (6 January).
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] With 3,500 cases including 865 fatal ones in Orenburg province, the epidemic stopped by February 1830.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The second cholera pandemic spread from the Russian Empire to the rest of Europe, claiming hundreds of thousands of lives.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] By 1831, the epidemic had infiltrated Russia's main cities and towns.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Russian soldiers brought the disease to Poland in February 1831.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] There were reported to have been 250,000 cases of cholera and 100,000 deaths in Russia.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In 1831, it is estimated that up to 100,000 deaths occurred in the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The cholera epidemic struck Warsaw during the November Uprising between 16 May and 20 August 1831; 4,734 people fell ill and 2,524 died.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The epidemic of cholera brought to Poland and East Prussia by Russian soldiers forced Prussian authorities to close their borders to Russian transports.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] There were Cholera Riots in the Russian Empire caused by the government's anticholera measures.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] By early 1831, frequent reports of the spread of the pandemic in Russia prompted the British government to issue quarantine orders for ships sailing from Russia to British ports.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] From September 1831 to January 1832, a catastrophic cholera epidemic ravaged the lower Euphrates and Tigris regions of what is now Iraq and Iran.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In Shushtar, Iran, about half of the city's inhabitants died from cholera.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The Mandaean community was hit particularly hard, and all of their priests died in the plague.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Yahya Bihram told Julius Heinrich Petermann that there were only 1,500 Mandaean survivors after the plague.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The epidemic reached Great Britain in October 1831, appearing in Sunderland, where it was carried by passengers on a ship from the Baltic.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] It also appeared in Gateshead and Newcastle.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In London, the disease claimed 6,536 victims; in Paris, 20,000 died (out of a population of 650,000), with about 100,000 deaths in all of France.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In 1832, the epidemic reached Quebec, Ontario, and Nova Scotia in Canada and Detroit and New York City in the United States.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] It reached the Pacific coast of North America between 1832 and 1834.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The pandemic prompted the passage of the landmark Public Health Act 1848 (11 & 12 Vict. c.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] 63), the Nuisances Removal and Diseases Prevention Act 1848 (11 & 12 Vict. c.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] 123) and the Nuisances Removal and Diseases Prevention Amendment Act 1849 (12 & 13 Vict. c.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In mid-1832, 57 Irish immigrants died who had been laying a stretch of railroad called Duffy's Cut, 30 miles west of Philadelphia.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In France, doctors believed cholera was associated with the poverty of certain communities or poor environment.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Russians believed the disease was contagious, although doctors did not understand how it spread.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] The United States believed that cholera was brought by recent immigrants, specifically the Irish, and epidemiologists understand they were carrying disease from British ports.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Lastly, the British thought the disease might rise from divine intervention.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Norwegian poet Henrik Wergeland wrote a stage play inspired by the pandemic, which had reached Norway.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In *The Indian Cholera* (*Den indiske Cholera*, 1835), he set his play in Colonial India, lambasting the poor response to the pandemic by authorities.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In response to the second cholera pandemic, the Ottoman Empire and Egypt reformed their quarantine systems, following the western Mediterranean model.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In 1831, the Egyptian Quarantine Board was established.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] It constructed Egypt’s first modern lazaretto in Alexandria in 1833.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In 1831, the Ottoman government set up the first permanent quarantine complex in Istanbul.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] In 1838, the Ottoman government established the Supreme Council of Health, which oversaw 59 quarantines.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] While largely useless against cholera, these quarantines shored up the two countries' epidemiological defenses against bubonic plague.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] As a result of the epidemic, the medical community developed a major advance, the intravenous saline drip.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] Latta established from blood studies that a saline drip greatly improved the condition of patients and saved many lives by preventing dehydration.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] A major outbreak in Sligo, Ireland, was reported on by Charlotte Thornley; her son, Bram Stoker, later incorporated some of her stories about the epidemic into his literature, such as "The Invisible Giant" in *Under the Sunset*.
[src:detroit/1826-1837-cholera-pandemic] It is also believed to have inspired the plague which Count Dracula brings to the town of Whitby in his novel *Dracula*.
[src:detroit/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:detroit/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:detroit/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:detroit/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:detroit/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:detroit/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:detroit/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:detroit/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:detroit/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:detroit/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 1701, French explorers Antoine de la Mothe Cadillac and Alphonse de Tonty founded Fort Pontchartrain du Détroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, it became an important industrial hub at the center of the Great Lakes region.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city's population rose to be the fourth-largest in the nation by 1920, with the expansion of the automotive industry in the early 20th century.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] One of its main features, the Detroit River, became the busiest commercial hub in the world.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In the mid-20th century, Detroit entered a state of urban decay that has continued to the present, as a result of industrial restructuring, the loss of jobs in the auto industry, and rapid suburbanization.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Since reaching a peak of 1.85 million at the 1950 census, Detroit's population has declined by more than 65 percent.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 2013, Detroit became the largest U.S. city to file for bankruptcy, but successfully exited in 2014.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Census Bureau reported that Detroit's population grew for a second consecutive year and led population growth in Michigan for the first time since the 1950s.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit is a port on the Detroit River, one of the four major straits that connect the Great Lakes system to the St.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city anchors the third-largest regional economy in the Midwest and the 16th-largest in the United States.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] It is also best known as the center of the U.S. automotive industry, and the "Big Three" auto manufacturers—General Motors, Ford, and Stellantis North America (Chrysler)—are all headquartered in Metro Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] It houses the Detroit Metropolitan Airport, one of the most important hub airports in the United States.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit and the adjacent Canadian city of Windsor constitute the second-busiest international crossing in North America, after San Diego–Tijuana.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit's culture is marked with diversity, having both local and international influences.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit gave rise to the music genres of Motown and techno, and also played an important role in the development of jazz, hip-hop, rock, and punk.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] As a result of the city's rapid growth in its boom years, Detroit has many globally unique architectural monuments and historic places.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Since the 2000s, conservation efforts have managed to save many architectural pieces and achieve several large-scale revitalizations, including the restoration of several historic theaters and entertainment venues, high-rise renovations, new sports stadiums, and a riverfront revitalization project.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit is an increasingly popular tourist destination which caters to about 16 million visitors per year.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 2015, Detroit was designated a "City of Design" by UNESCO, the first and only U.S. city to receive this designation.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit is named after the Detroit River, connecting Lake St.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The name comes from the French language word *détroit* meaning 'strait' as the city was situated on a narrow north–south passage of water linking the two lakes.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The river was known as *le détroit du Lac Érié* in the French language, which means 'the strait of Lake Erie'.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In historical contexts, the strait included Lake St.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Throughout its history, Detroit has been known by several nicknames.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Its founder, Antoine de la Mothe Cadillac, originally envisioned the settlement as a major city within the Pays d'en Haut, calling it the *Paris de la Nouvelle-France*, (*Paris of New France*).
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] As the city evolved into the world's automotive center, "Detroit" became a metonym for the industry itself.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Its status as the heart of the automotive world is reflected in the nickname *Motor City*, while its deep musical legacy is famously celebrated through the moniker *Motown*.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Other nicknames emerged during the 20th century to reflect different aspects of the city's identity.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] It became known as the *City of Champions* in the 1930s following a series of sports successes, while the Detroit Red Wings later trademarked the name *Hockeytown*.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In more recent years, it has been called the *Renaissance City*, a nod to its urban revitalization efforts and the iconic Renaissance Center complex.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Paleo-Indians inhabited areas near Detroit as early as 11,000 years ago including the culture referred to as the Mound Builders.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By the 17th century, the region was inhabited by Huron, Odawa, Potawatomi, and Iroquois peoples.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The area is known by the Anishinaabe people as *Waawiiyaataanong*, translating to 'where the water curves around'.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The first Europeans did not penetrate into the region and reach the straits of Detroit until French missionaries and traders worked their way around the Iroquois League, with whom they were at war in the 1630s.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The Huron and Neutral people held the north side of Lake Erie until the 1650s, when the Iroquois pushed them and the Erie people away from the lake and its beaver-rich feeder streams in the Beaver Wars of 1649–1655.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By the 1670s, the war-weakened Iroquois laid claim to as far south as the Ohio River valley in northern Kentucky as hunting grounds, and had absorbed many other Iroquoian peoples after defeating them in war.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] For the next hundred years, virtually no British or French action was contemplated without consultation with the Iroquois or consideration of their likely response.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] On July 24, 1701, the French explorer Antoine de la Mothe Cadillac (1658–1730), with his lieutenant Alphonse de Tonty (1659–1727), and more than a hundred other Royal French settlers traveling south and west from New France (modern Province of Quebec), along the St.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Lawrence River valley to the Great Lakes region, began constructing a small fort on the north bank of the Detroit River.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Cadillac named the settlement Fort Pontchartrain du Détroit, after Louis Phélypeaux, comte de Pontchartrain (1643–1727), the Secretary of State of the Navy under King Louis XIV (1638–1715).
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Sainte-Anne de Détroit was founded on July 26 and is the second-oldest continuously operating Roman Catholic parish in the United States.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The region's then colonial economy was based on the lucrative fur trade, in which numerous Native American peoples had important roles as trappers and traders.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] During the French and Indian War (1753–63)—the North American front of the Seven Years' War in Europe between the Kingdom of Great Britain and the Kingdom of France—British troops gained control of the settlement a few years into the conflict in 1760 and shortened its name to Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Several regional Native American tribes, such as the Potowatomi, Ojibwe and Huron, launched Pontiac's War (1763–1766), and laid siege in 1763 to Fort Detroit along the Detroit River in the Great Lakes but failed to capture it.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In defeat, France ceded its territory in North America of New France and south of the lakes east of the Mississippi to the Appalachian Mountains to Britain following the war.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] When Great Britain evicted France from its colonial possessions in New France (Canada) in the peace terms of the Treaty of Paris of 1763, it also removed one barrier to American colonists migrating west across the mountains.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] British negotiations with the Iroquois would both prove critical and lead to the Royal Proclamation of 1763, which limited settlements South of and below the Great Lakes and west of the Alleghenies / Appalachians.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Many colonists and pioneers in the Thirteen Colonies along the East Coast, resented and then simply defied this restraint, later becoming supporters of the rebellious American Revolution.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By 1773, after the addition of increasing numbers of the Anglo-American settlers, the population of Detroit and Fort Detroit, was edging up to 1,400 (doubled in the previous decade).
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By 1778, its population had doubled again, reaching 2,144 and it was the third-largest town in what was known then as the Province of Quebec since the British takeover of former French colonial possessions in North America in 1763.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The new Northwest Territories established the southern border with Great Britain's remaining colonial provinces in British North America and became provinces of Upper Canada and Lower Canada.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] However, the disputed border area remained under British control with several military forts and trading posts for another decade, and its forces did not fully withdraw until 1796, following the negotiations and ratification of the subsequent Jay Treaty of 1794 between the British and Americans.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, white American settlers began pouring westwards across the Appalachians and through the Great Lakes.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Today the municipal flag of Detroit reflects both its French and English colonial heritage.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Descendants of the earliest French and French-Canadian settlers formed a cohesive community, who gradually were superseded as the dominant population after more Anglo-American settlers arrived in the early 19th century with American westward migration.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Clair and south to Monroe and downriver suburbs, the ethnic French Canadians of Detroit remain a subculture in the region up into the 21st century.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] After the Great Fire of 1805 destroyed nearly all of Detroit's colonial buildings, the town was quickly rebuilt with aid from both local residents and those from Quebec.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The town of Detroit was first incorporated as a city in 1806, but the incorporation was repealed just three years later.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] It was reincorporated in 1815 following the War of 1812.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 1824, the city held its first mayoral election, with John R.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Williams becoming the first elected mayor.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Following Michigan's admission to the Union in 1837, Detroit served as the state's first capital and hosted the inaugural state elections that same year.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Between 1815 and 1900, the city borders expanded significantly through the annexation of land from surrounding townships, such as Hamtramck, Springwells, Greenfield, and Grosse Pointe, before many of those townships incorporated as independent cities in the 20th century.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Public land sales began in 1818, and by 1836, the city formalized its public water supply by establishing a municipal water works.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] It followed the end of the second cholera pandemic that had devastated Detroit and many other North American cities.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city's population grew steadily throughout the 19th century, fueled by immigrants from Germany, Poland, Italy, Greece, and Belgium.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By the 1830s, Germans had become the city's predominant ethnic group.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] During the Irish Great Famine of the 1840s, a wave of Irish immigrants arrived, settling primarily in the Corktown neighborhood.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit's Black population remained small during the 19th century; it constituted less than four percent of the city's population by the time of the 1863 race riot during the Civil War, numbering roughly 1,500 to 1,600 residents.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit's unique geography provided easy access to raw materials like iron ore, copper, coal, and timber.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Coupled with the opening of the Erie Canal in 1825, this proximity shifted the city's local economy toward heavy industries such as machinery, metalworking, and engine production in the mid-19th century.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Well before the automotive era, the city led the nation in the construction of railroad cars and freighters; the Michigan-Peninsular Car Company was the city's largest manufacturer during that period, while the Detroit Dry Dock Company built hulls for the largest ships on the Great Lakes.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By the 1870s, cast-iron stoves manufacturing had become Detroit's largest single industry.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city also became a major producer of pharmaceuticals, seeds, tobacco, and beer, with companies like the Ferry-Morse Seed Company and pharmaceutical companies Parke-Davis and Frederick Stearns & Co. emerging as national industry leaders.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The Detroit International Exposition and Fair (1889–1892) showcased the city's expanding economy in the late 19th century.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit saw explosive growth in the auto industry in the early 20th century.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 1913, Henry Ford's moving assembly line revolutionized automotive manufacturing, reducing chassis assembly time by nearly 90%.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] This efficiency enabled low-cost mass production, with a new Model T rolling off the line every 24 seconds at peak capacity.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By 1920, Detroit's automakers, including Ford, Buick (GM), Chevrolet (GM), Dodge Brothers (Chrysler), and Maxwell (Chrysler), were producing one million cars annually, accounting for roughly half of the world's total production.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city was undoubtedly the automotive capital of the world.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Even before the rise of the auto industry, Detroit was already a primary gateway for iron ore, coal, and grain moving through the Great Lakes.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Its shipping tonnage frequently exceeded that of the world's major saltwater ports; in 1907 alone, the Detroit River carried over 67 million tons of cargo, surpassing that of the ports of London (18.7 million) and New York City (20.4 million) combined.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The subsequent surge in auto production after 1914 fueled a parallel expansion in the city's commerce.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] However, the increasing traffic at the Detroit-Windsor crossing frequently caused bottlenecks, as railroads and automobiles still relied on slow ferries.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The opening of the Michigan Central Railway Tunnel, the Ambassador Bridge, and the Detroit–Windsor Tunnel largely replaced these ferries, significantly reducing the shipment and storage costs of essential commodities.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Between 1900 and 1930, the city's population more than quintupled, soaring from roughly 285,000 to 1.6 million.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By 1950, Detroit's population peaked at 1.85 million, making it the fifth-largest city in the U.S.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] At the time, residents enjoyed the highest per capita income in the country, driven by high-paying manufacturing jobs in the booming automotive industry.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In fact, a typical Ford worker earned an annual wage more than twice the national median.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] During this era, Detroit also maintained a lower poverty rate than its suburbs.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] With a median household income approximately 20% above the national number and one of the highest homeownership rates in the country, Detroit was the wealthiest city in the U.S. and, by some accounts, had the highest standard of living in the world.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The Great Depression hit Detroit hard as car sales plummeted, leading to mass unemployment.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city saw the formation of several labor unions, notably the United Auto Workers, founded in Detroit in 1935.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Around this same time, the Teamsters strengthened their Detroit operations in the early 1930s, largely through James Hoffa's organizing of warehouse and freight drivers.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] As the city emerged from the Depression, racial tensions escalated between white residents and Black Southerners who had arrived during the Great Migration.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] This friction, fueled by intense competition for jobs and housing, eventually culminated in the 1943 race riot.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] During World War II, the U.S. government encouraged the retooling of the auto industry to support the Allies.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Civilian car production ceased from 1942 to 1945 as factories shifted to manufacturing military equipment.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Despite having only 2% of the U.S. population, the city produced over 10% of all American war materiel, while the broader Detroit metro region accounted for nearly 30% of the nation's total output.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] This staggering output was led by the Detroit Assembly and the Detroit Tank Arsenal, which together produced nearly as many tanks as all of Nazi Germany.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] (below) were among many Detroit auto factories that closed during the industrial deconcentration in the 1950s.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The first signs of Detroit's decline appeared in the 1950s with the onset of industrial deconcentration and suburbanization.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The Packard Automotive Plant closed during that decade, and the massive Hudson Motor Plant at East Jefferson and Conner was largely demolished by 1961.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Studebaker ended its manufacturing presence in Detroit in 1956, and Kaiser-Frazer ceased local passenger car production in the mid-1950s.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 1961, under the Louis Miriani administration, the city recorded its first post-war budget deficit of $16 million.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] This shortfall resulted from a sharp decline in tax revenue as major industries and residents moved to the suburbs.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Since its 1950 peak of 1.85 million, Detroit has lost 65% of its population.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] As the city's overall population declined, its Black population nearly doubled between 1950 and 1970, and the city officially became majority-Black in the 1970s.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Most migrated from the Deep South, drawn by auto industry jobs.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] However, these newcomers were often relegated to lower-paying roles, while higher-paying positions remained dominated by longtime white residents.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Furthermore, discriminatory redlining policies frequently denied them access to essential financial services.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] This era was defined by the civil rights movement; notably, in June 1963, Dr.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Martin Luther King Jr. delivered a major speech during the Detroit Walk to Freedom that foreshadowed his "I Have a Dream" speech in Washington, D.C., just two months later.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Despite the passage of federal civil rights legislation, deep-seated racial tensions ignited the 12th Street Riot in 1967, which remains one of the deadliest and costliest civil disturbances in U.S. history.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 1973, Coleman Young was elected as Detroit's first Black mayor.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Throughout his 20-year tenure, the city's economy continued to deteriorate as businesses and residents fled.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Early in his first term, Young faced a looming "near-bankruptcy" situation.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] To maintain a balanced budget, he implemented aggressive tax increases and spending cuts.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] During the recession of the early 1980s, triggered by the 1979 oil crisis, the automotive industry suffered massive layoffs, leaving Detroit with a $119 million deficit by 1981.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] To avoid bankruptcy, Young successfully campaigned for an income tax hike and sold up to $125 million in emergency bonds.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By his final year in office in 1993–94, the city faced a $271 million deficit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] To address this, Young mandated a 10% salary cut for city employees before leaving office.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit has lacked high-capacity mass transit since 1956, when its primary streetcar system was dismantled.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Following mounting pressure for rapid transit, a 1972 study recommended a system connecting Downtown, Midtown, and suburbs like Dearborn, Southfield, and the Detroit Metro Airport.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] President Gerald Ford offered the Detroit region $600 million in federal funding to build a robust mass transit system that included a subway and suburban commuter rail.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] However, local disagreements over project details and regional control delayed implementation for years, leading the Reagan administration to withdraw the funding in the early 1980s.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By 1987, only the 2.9-mile People Mover loop was completed, serving as a fragment of the originally envisioned broader network.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Dennis Archer became Detroit's 67th mayor in January 1994, succeeding Coleman Young.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] While the city tax base continued to shrink with a declining population, the Archer administration was able to revitalize its finances.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Inheriting an $88 million deficit, Archer balanced the budget within his first year through rigorous fiscal reforms.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] He streamlined the payroll by eliminating hundreds of municipal position through attrition and deployed "turnaround teams" of outside business experts to improve city services.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Under the Archer administration, Detroit stabilized its credit rating and achieved a streak of consistent budget surpluses.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] To diversify Detroit's tax base and retain revenue that was otherwise flowing to the nearby city of Windsor, a statewide initiative was proposed and passed in 1996 to allow casino gambling in Detroit, leading to the opening of three privately owned casinos in the downtown area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Starting in the mid-2000s, the city relied heavily on borrowing to address persistent budget gaps and pension liabilities, including $1.4 billion in 2005 alone.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] This initiated a seven-year streak of annual deficits, each exceeding $150 million.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The then-Mayor, Kwame Kilpatrick, was forced to resign in 2008 after felony convictions, and was later sentenced to 28 years in federal prison.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] His actions were estimated to have cost the city approximately $20 million.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Census recorded Detroit's largest single-decade population drop in its history, at approximately 25%.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] This severe population decline resulted in a massive reduction in state revenue sharing, as constitutional revenue sharing is distributed on a per capita basis.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Furthermore, foreclosures caused by unemployment reduced property values across the city following the Great Recession, further reducing the tax base.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 2011, the city government recorded that roughly half of its 305,000 property owners failed to pay their taxes, leaving over $246 million uncollected.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] By 2013, Detroit faced a $327 million budget deficit and more than $18 billion in total long-term debt and liabilities.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Facing a financial crisis, then-Mayor Dave Bing and the City Council accepted state oversight in exchange for financial aid from the state.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In March 2013, Michigan Governor Rick Snyder declared a financial emergency in Detroit, leading the Local Emergency Financial Assistance Loan Board to appoint Kevyn Orr as the city’s emergency manager.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] After negotiations for cuts failed, Orr announced on June 14 that Detroit would default on approximately $2.5 billion in unsecured debt and skipped a $39.7 million interest payment.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] On July 18, 2013, Detroit became the largest U.S. city by population to file for Chapter 9 bankruptcy.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 2014, Mike Duggan, the former CEO of the Detroit Medical Center, was elected mayor as the city exited bankruptcy in December, having cut $7 billion in debt and invested $1.7 billion in services.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] To reduce operating costs between 2012 and 2015, Detroit cut its full-time workforce by nearly 40%.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] It also eliminated annual maintenance and operation expenses for Belle Isle by leasing the park to the state.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The lease is set for 30 years, with the option for two 15-year renewals.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Additionally, the Detroit Institute of Arts became a private organization to help fund the city's recovery following legal battles.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Following its bankruptcy exit, Detroit has stabilized its finances with a string of budget surpluses under the Duggan administration.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city now maintains roughly $550 million in reserves.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] These funds are earmarked for the city’s rainy day fund, retiree protection, and various liability funds to mitigate potential economic slumps.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city resumed payments to its two pension funds in 2024, ending a nine-year period during which the state of Michigan and private organizations handled those contributions.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Since 2014, the city's neighborhoods have witnessed the demolition of over 27,000 dangerous, long-abandoned residential structures that had become hotbeds for criminal activity.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Additionally, efforts have been made to enhance city services, including improvements to emergency response times, bus services, and the replacement of tens of thousands of non-functional streetlights with LED light.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Downtown Detroit, which had long been neglected, has seen numerous new developments through public-private partnerships.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Since 2014, many abandoned or underutilized landmark buildings in the downtown area have been revitalized through the city's subsidized programs and private investments.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city's streetcar system, QLine, opened for public use in May 2017.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The construction of Little Caesars Arena and Hudson's Detroit has attracted many small businesses, including shops and restaurants along Woodward Avenue.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The long-vacant Michigan Central Station was purchased by the Ford Motor Company in 2018 and is being redeveloped into the company's new campus, driving the revitalization of the surrounding Corktown area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] After more than half a century of population decline, the city experienced its first population growth since the late 1950s in 2024, recording a higher growth rate than any other city in the state.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 2025, the United States Census Bureau reported that Detroit's population had increased for the second consecutive year.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In January 2026, Mary Sheffield, the former president of the Detroit City Council, was sworn in as the city's 76th mayor.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] She is the first woman to be elected to the office.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] While Detroit has seen gains in city finances and investor confidence, it still lags significantly behind national standards for income and education.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] It remains the poorest large city in the United States, with half of its children living in poverty.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 2024, the city's median household income was less than half the national number.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Education remains a critical challenge; despite having high per-pupil funding, the Detroit Public Schools ranked last among 26 large urban districts.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Proficiency in reading and math stands at less than 10% for both fourth and eighth graders, and 61% of students were chronically absent during the 2024–25 school year.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 142.87 square miles (370.03 km2), of which 138.75 square miles (359.36 km2) is land and 4.12 square miles (10.67 km2) is water.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit is the principal city in Metro Detroit and Southeast Michigan.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] It is situated in the Midwestern United States and the Great Lakes region.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The Detroit River International Wildlife Refuge is the only international wildlife preserve in North America and is uniquely located in the heart of a major metropolitan area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The refuge includes islands, coastal wetlands, marshes, shoals, and waterfront lands along 48 miles (77 km) of the Detroit River and western Lake Erie shoreline.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city slopes gently from the northwest to southeast on a till plain composed largely of glacial and lake clay.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The most notable topographical feature in the city is the Detroit Moraine, a broad clay ridge on which the older portions of Detroit and Windsor are located, rising approximately 62 feet (19 m) above the river at its highest point.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The highest elevation in the city is directly north of Gorham Playground on the northwest side approximately three blocks south of 8 Mile Road, at a height of 675 to 680 feet (206 to 207 m).
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit's lowest elevation is along the Detroit River, at a surface height of 572 feet (174 m).
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit's waterfront showcases a variety of architectural styles, with the postmodern Neo-Gothic spires of Ally Detroit Center paying homage to the city's Art Deco skyscrapers.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Together with the Renaissance Center, these buildings form a distinctive and recognizable skyline.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Examples of the Art Deco style include the Guardian Building and Penobscot Building downtown, as well as the Fisher Building and Cadillac Place in New Center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Prominent cultural landmarks from the early 20th century include the Fox Theatre, Detroit Opera House, and Detroit Institute of Arts.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] While Downtown Detroit and New Center feature high-rise buildings, much of Detroit consists of low-rise structures and single-family homes.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Residential high-rises are concentrated in upscale neighborhoods such as the East Riverfront, extending toward Grosse Pointe, and Palmer Park.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The University Commons-Palmer Park district anchors historic areas including Palmer Woods, Sherwood Forest, and the University District near the University of Detroit Mercy.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] 42 significant structures in the city are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Multi-million dollar restorations and new developments have revitalized neighborhoods such as West Canfield and Brush Park.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city has one of the United States' largest surviving collections of late 19th- and early 20th-century buildings.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Architecturally significant churches and cathedrals in the city include St.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Mary's, the Sweetest Heart of Mary, and the Cathedral of the Most Blessed Sacrament.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Historic preservation efforts continue to thrive, with downtown redevelopment projects revitalizing parts of the city, among them Campus Martius Park, Grand Circus Park near the city's theater district, Ford Field, Comerica Park, and Little Caesars Arena.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit has a variety of neighborhood types.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The revitalized Downtown, Midtown, Corktown, New Center areas feature many historic buildings and are high density, while further out, particularly in the northeast and on the fringes, high vacancy levels are problematic, for which a number of solutions have been proposed.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 2007, Downtown Detroit was recognized as the best city neighborhood in which to retire among the United States' largest metro areas by CNNMoney editors.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Lafayette Park is a revitalized neighborhood on the city's east side, part of the Ludwig Mies van der Rohe residential district.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The 78-acre (32 ha) development was originally called the Gratiot Park.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Planned by Mies van der Rohe, Ludwig Hilberseimer and Alfred Caldwell it includes a landscaped, 19-acre (7.7 ha) park with no through traffic, in which these and other low-rise apartment buildings are situated.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Immigrants have contributed to the city's neighborhood revitalization, especially in southwest Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Southwest Detroit has experienced a thriving economy in recent years, as evidenced by new housing, increased business openings and the recently opened Mexicantown International Welcome Center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city has numerous neighborhoods consisting of vacant properties resulting in low inhabited density in those areas, stretching city services and infrastructure.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] These neighborhoods are concentrated in the northeast and on the city's fringes.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] A 2009 parcel survey found about a quarter of residential lots in the city to be undeveloped or vacant, and about 10% of the city's housing to be unoccupied.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The survey also reported that most (86%) of the city's homes are in good condition with a minority (9%) in fair condition needing only minor repairs.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] To deal with vacancy issues, the city has begun demolishing the derelict houses, razing 3,000 of the total 10,000 in 2010, but the resulting low density creates a strain on the city's infrastructure.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] To remedy this, a number of solutions have been proposed including resident relocation from more sparsely populated neighborhoods and converting unused space to urban agricultural use, including Hantz Woodlands, though the city expects to be in the planning stages for up to another two years.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Public funding and private investment have been made with promises to rehabilitate neighborhoods.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In April 2008, the city announced a $300 million (~$428 million in 2024) stimulus plan to create jobs and revitalize neighborhoods, financed by city bonds and paid for by earmarking about 15% of the wagering tax.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The city's working plans for neighborhood revitalizations include 7-Mile/Livernois, Brightmoor, East English Village, Grand River/Greenfield, North End, and Osborn.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Private organizations have pledged substantial funding to the efforts.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Additionally, the city has cleared a 1,200-acre (490 ha) section of land for large-scale neighborhood construction, which the city is calling the *Far Eastside Plan*.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In 2011, Mayor Dave Bing announced a plan to categorize neighborhoods by their needs and prioritize the most needed services for those neighborhoods.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit Parks & Recreation maintains 308 public parks, covering 4,950 acres (2,003 ha), or about 5.6% of the city's land area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Grand Circus Park, established in 1847 as part of the original Woodward plan, was the city's first official municipal park.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Other major parks include Campus Martius, Belle Isle, River Rouge, Palmer, and Chene Park.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The Detroit International Riverfront also serves as a key recreation space, featuring a 3.5-mile promenade from Hart Plaza to Belle Isle, with a second phase planned to extend the promenade to the Ambassador Bridge.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] In the surrounding Metro Area, the Huron–Clinton Metroparks system (established in 1940) includes 13 regional parks.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] These span over 24,000 acres (97 km2) along the Huron and Clinton Rivers.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Detroit is also renowned for its outdoor public art.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Many of its fountains serve as monumental landmarks, including the Bagley Memorial Fountain, the Horace E.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Dodge and Son Memorial Fountain in Hart Plaza, and the James Scott Memorial Fountain on Belle Isle.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] An important civic sculpture is *The Spirit of Detroit* by Marshall Fredericks at the Coleman Young Municipal Center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The image is often used as a symbol of Detroit, and the statue is occasionally dressed in sports jerseys to celebrate when a Detroit team is doing well.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] A memorial to Joe Louis is located at the intersection of Jefferson and Woodward Avenues.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The sculpture, commissioned by *Sports Illustrated* and executed by Robert Graham, is a 24-foot (7.3 m) long arm with a fist suspended by a pyramidal framework.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Winters are cold, with moderate snowfall and temperatures not rising above freezing on an average 44 days annually, while dropping to or below 0 °F (−18 °C) on an average 4.4 days a year; summers are warm to hot with temperatures exceeding 90 °F (32 °C) on 12 days.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The warm season runs from May to September.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The monthly daily mean temperature ranges from 25.6 °F (−3.6 °C) in January to 73.6 °F (23.1 °C) in July.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Official temperature extremes range from 105 °F (41 °C) on July 24, 1934, down to −21 °F (−29 °C) on January 21, 1984; the record low maximum is −4 °F (−20 °C) on January 19, 1994, while, conversely the record high minimum is 80 °F (27 °C) on August 1, 2006, the most recent of five occurrences.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] A decade or two may pass between readings of 100 °F (38 °C) or higher, which last occurred July 17, 2012.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] The average window for freezing temperatures is October 20 through April 22, allowing a growing season of 180 days.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Precipitation is moderate and somewhat evenly distributed throughout the year, although the warmer months such as May and June average more, averaging 33.5 inches (850 mm) annually, but historically ranging from 20.49 in (520 mm) in 1963 to 47.70 in (1,212 mm) in 2011.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Snowfall, which typically falls in measurable amounts between November 15 through April 4 (occasionally in October and very rarely in May), averages 42.5 inches (108 cm) per season, although historically ranging from 11.5 in (29 cm) in 1881–82 to 94.9 in (241 cm) in 2013–14.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] A thick layer of snow is not often seen, with an average of only 27.5 days with 3 in (7.6 cm) or more of snow cover.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] Thunderstorms are frequent in the Detroit area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p01] These usually occur during spring and summer.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In the 2020 United States census, the city had 639,111 residents, ranking it the 27th-most populous city in the US.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Of the large shrinking cities in the US, Detroit has had the most dramatic decline in the population of the past 70 years (down 1,210,457) and the second-largest percentage decline (down 65.4%).
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] While the drop in Detroit's population has been ongoing since 1950, the most dramatic period was the significant 25% decline between the 2000 and 2010 census.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The population density was 5,144.3 people per square mile (1,986.2 people/km2).
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] There were 349,170 housing units at an average density of 2,516.5 units per square mile (971.6 units/km2).
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Beginning with the rise of the automobile industry, Detroit's population increased more than sixfold during the first half of the 20th century as an influx of European (Polish, German), Middle Eastern (Lebanese, Assyrian), and Southern migrants brought their families to the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] With this economic boom following World War I, the African American population grew from a mere 6,000 in 1910 to more than 120,000 by 1930.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Perhaps one of the most overt examples of neighborhood discrimination occurred in 1925 when African American physician Ossian Sweet found his home surrounded by an angry mob of his hostile white neighbors violently protesting his new move into a traditionally white neighborhood.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Sweet and ten of his family members and friends were put on trial for murder as one of the mob members throwing rocks at the newly purchased house was shot and killed by someone firing out of a second-floor window.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit has a relatively large Mexican-American population.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In the early 20th century, thousands of Mexicans came to Detroit to work in agricultural, automotive, and steel jobs.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] During the Mexican Repatriation of the 1930s many Mexicans in Detroit were willingly repatriated or forced to repatriate.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] By the 1940s much of the Mexican community began to settle what is now Mexicantown.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Immigration from Jalisco significantly increased the Latino population in the 1990s.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Per the 2023 American Community Survey five-year estimates, the Mexican American population was 35,273 comprising over 75% of the Latino population with Puerto Ricans as the next largest group at 5,887.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] After World War II, many people from Appalachia also settled in Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Appalachians formed communities and their children acquired southern accents.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Many Lithuanians also settled in Detroit during the World War II era, especially on the city's Southwest side in the West Vernor area, where the renovated Lithuanian Hall reopened in 2006.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] While African Americans in 2020 comprised 13.5% of Michigan's population, they made up nearly 77.2% of Detroit's population.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The next largest population groups were non-Hispanic whites, at 10.1%, and Hispanics, at 8.0%.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2001, 103,000 Jews, or about 1.9% of the population, were living in the Detroit area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] According to the 2010 census, segregation in Detroit decreased in absolute and relative terms and in the first decade of the 21st century, about two-thirds of the total black population in the metropolitan area resided within the city limits of Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The number of integrated neighborhoods increased from 100 in 2000 to 204 in 2010.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] After being ranked the most segregated metropolitan area in the United States in 2000, Detroit was ranked fourth most-segregated in 2010.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] A 2011 op-ed in *The New York Times* attributed the decreased segregation rating to the overall exodus from the city, cautioning that these areas may soon become more segregated.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] There are four areas of Detroit with significant Asian and Asian American populations.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Northeast Detroit has a large population of Hmong with a smaller group of Lao people.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] A portion of Detroit next to eastern Hamtramck includes Bangladeshi Americans, Indian Americans, and Pakistani Americans; nearly all of the Bangladeshi population in Detroit lives in that area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The area north of downtown has transient Asian national origin residents who are university students or hospital workers.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Few of them have permanent residency after schooling ends.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] They are mostly Chinese and Indian but the population also includes Filipinos, Koreans, and Pakistanis.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In Southwest and western Detroit there are smaller, scattered Asian communities.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] According to a 2014 study, 67% of the population of the city identified themselves as Christians, with 49% professing adherence to Protestant churches, and 16% professing Roman Catholic beliefs, while 24% claim no religious affiliation.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Other religions collectively make up about 8% of the population.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] There was a wide distribution of age in the city, with 31.1% under the age of 18, 9.7% from 18 to 24, 29.5% from 25 to 44, 19.3% from 45 to 64, and 10.4% 65 years of age or older.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] For every 100 females, there were 89.1 males.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 83.5 males.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit's 639,111 residents represent 269,445 households, and 162,924 families residing in the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The average household size was 2.59, and the average family size was 3.36.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The loss of industrial and working-class jobs in the city has resulted in high rates of poverty and associated problems.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] From 2000 to 2009, the city's estimated median household income fell from $29,526 to $26,098.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] As of 2010, the mean income of Detroit is below the overall U.S. average by several thousand dollars.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Of every three Detroit residents, one lives in poverty.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Luke Bergmann, author of *Getting Ghost: Two Young Lives and the Struggle for the Soul of an American City*, said in 2010, "Detroit is now one of the poorest big cities in the country".
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In the 2018 American Community Survey, median household income in the city was $31,283, compared with the median for Michigan of $56,697.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The median income for a family was $36,842, well below the state median of $72,036.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] 33.4% of families had income at or below the federally defined poverty level.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Out of the total population, 47.3% of those under the age of 18 and 21.0% of those 65 and older had income at or below the federally defined poverty line.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city of Detroit has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2016, 24.7% of Detroit households lacked a car, much higher than the national average of 8.7%.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit averaged 1.15 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit has gained notoriety for its high amount of crime, having struggled with it for decades.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The number of homicides in 1974 was 714.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The homicide rate in 2022 was the third highest in the nation at 50.0 per 100,000.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Downtown typically has lower crime than national and state averages.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] According to a 2007 analysis, Detroit officials note about 65 to 70 percent of homicides in the city were drug related, with the rate of unsolved murders roughly 70%.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Although the rate of violent crime dropped 11% in 2008, violent crime in Detroit has not declined as much as the national average from 2007 to 2011.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The violent crime rate is one of the highest in the United States.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] "Neighborhoodscout.com" reported a crime rate of 62.18 per 1,000 residents for property crimes, and 16.73 per 1,000 for violent crimes (compared to national figures of 32 per 1,000 for property crimes and 5 per 1,000 for violent crime in 2008).
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2012, crime in the city was among the reasons for more expensive car insurance.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Areas of the city adjacent to the Detroit River are also patrolled by the United States Border Patrol.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Several major corporations are based in the city, including three Fortune 500 companies.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The most heavily represented sectors are manufacturing (particularly automotive), finance, technology, and health care.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The most significant companies based in Detroit include General Motors, Rocket Mortgage, Ally Financial, Compuware, Shinola, American Axle, Little Caesars, DTE Energy, Lowe Campbell Ewald, Blue Cross Blue Shield of Michigan, and Rossetti Architects.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] About 80,500 people work in downtown Detroit, comprising one-fifth of the city's employment base.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Aside from the numerous Detroit-based companies listed above, downtown contains large offices for Comerica, Stellantis (formerly Chrysler), Fifth Third Bank, HP Enterprise, Deloitte, PricewaterhouseCoopers, KPMG, and Ernst & Young.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Ford Motor Company is in the adjacent city of Dearborn.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Thousands more employees work in Midtown, north of the central business district.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Midtown's anchors are the city's largest single employer Detroit Medical Center, Wayne State University, and the Henry Ford Health System in New Center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Midtown is also home to watchmaker Shinola and an array of small and startup companies.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] New Center bases TechTown, a research and business incubator hub that is part of the Wayne State University system.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Like downtown, Corktown Is experiencing growth with the new Ford Corktown Campus under development.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Many downtown employers are relatively new, as there has been a marked trend of companies moving from satellite suburbs into the downtown core.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Compuware completed its world headquarters in downtown in 2003.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] OnStar, Blue Cross Blue Shield, and HP Enterprise Services are at the Renaissance Center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] PricewaterhouseCoopers Plaza offices are adjacent to Ford Field, and Ernst & Young completed its office building at One Kennedy Square in 2006.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Perhaps most prominently, in 2010, Quicken Loans, one of the largest mortgage lenders, relocated its world headquarters and 4,000 employees to downtown Detroit, consolidating its suburban offices.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Patent and Trademark Office opened its Elijah J.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] McCoy Satellite Office in the Rivertown/Warehouse District as its first location outside Washington, D.C.'s metropolitan area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In April 2014, the United States Department of Labor reported the city's unemployment rate at 14.5%.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2023 the city of Detroit reported a poverty rate of 33.8%.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city has cleared sections of land while retaining some historically significant vacant buildings to spur redevelopment; even though it has struggled with finances, the city issued bonds in 2008 to provide funding for ongoing work to demolish blighted properties.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Two years earlier, downtown reported $1.3 billion in restorations and new developments which increased the number of construction jobs in the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In the decade prior to 2006, downtown gained more than $15 billion in new investment from private and public sectors.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Despite the city's recent financial issues, many developers remain unfazed by Detroit's problems.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Midtown is one of the most successful areas within Detroit to have a residential occupancy rate of 96%.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Numerous developments have been recently completed or are in various stages of construction.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Downtown's population of young professionals is growing, and retail is expanding.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] A study in 2007 found out that Downtown's new residents are predominantly young professionals (57% are ages 25 to 34, 45% have bachelor's degrees, and 34% have a master's or professional degree), a trend which has hastened over the last decade.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Since 2006, $9 billion has been invested in downtown and surrounding neighborhoods; $5.2 billion of which has come in 2013 and 2014.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Construction activity, particularly rehabilitation of historic downtown buildings, has increased markedly.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] As of 2014, the number of vacant downtown buildings has dropped from nearly 50 to around 13.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2013 Meijer, a midwestern retail chain, opened its first supercenter store in Detroit; this was a $20 million, 190,000-square-foot store in the northern portion of the city and it also is the centerpiece of a new $72 million shopping center named Gateway Marketplace.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2015 Meijer opened its second supercenter store in the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2019 JPMorgan Chase announced plans to invest $50 million more in affordable housing, job training, and entrepreneurship by the end of 2022, growing its investment to $200 million.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Near Zug Island, the southwest part of the city was developed over a 1,500-acre (610 ha) salt mine that is 1,100 feet (340 m) below the surface.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Detroit salt mine run by the Detroit Salt Company has over 100 miles (160 km) of roads within.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In the central portions of Detroit, the population of young professionals, artists, and other transplants is growing and retail is expanding.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] This dynamic is luring additional new residents, and former residents returning from other cities, to the city's Downtown along with the revitalized Midtown and New Center areas.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] A desire to be closer to the urban scene has attracted some young professionals to reside in inner ring suburbs such as Ferndale and Royal Oak.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The proximity to Windsor provides for views and nightlife, along with Ontario's minimum drinking age of 19.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] A 2011 study by Walk Score recognized Detroit for its above average walkability among large U.S. cities.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] About two-thirds of suburban residents occasionally dine and attend cultural events or take in professional games in the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Live music has been a prominent feature of Detroit's nightlife since the late 1940s, bringing the city recognition under the nickname "Motown".
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The metropolitan area has many nationally prominent live music venues.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Concerts hosted by Live Nation perform throughout the Detroit area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The theater venue circuit is the United States' second largest and hosts Broadway performances.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city has a rich musical heritage and has contributed to many genres over the decades.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Important music events include the Detroit International Jazz Festival, the Detroit Electronic Music Festival, the Motor City Music Conference (MC2), the Urban Organic Music Conference, the Concert of Colors, and the hip-hop Summer Jamz festival.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In the 1940s, Detroit blues artist John Lee Hooker became a long-term resident in the Delray neighborhood.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Hooker, among other important blues musicians, migrated from his home in Mississippi, bringing the Delta blues to Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Hooker recorded for Fortune Records, the biggest pre-Motown blues/soul label.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] During the 1950s, the city became a center for jazz, with stars performing in the Black Bottom neighborhood.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Prominent emerging jazz musicians included trumpeter Donald Byrd (who attended Cass Tech and performed with Art Blakey and the Jazz Messengers early in his career) and saxophonist Pepper Adams (who enjoyed a solo career and accompanied Byrd on several albums).
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Graystone International Jazz Museum documents jazz in Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Other prominent Motor City R&B stars in the 1950s and early 1960s were Nolan Strong, Andre Williams, and Nathaniel Mayer—who all scored local and national hits on the Fortune Records label.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] According to Smokey Robinson, Strong was a primary influence on his voice as a teenager.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Fortune label, a family-operated label on Third Avenue, was owned by the husband-and-wife team of Jack Brown and Devora Brown.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Fortune—which also released country, gospel and rockabilly LPs and 45s—laid the groundwork for Motown, which became Detroit's most legendary record label.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Artists were backed by in-house vocalists the Andantes and the Funk Brothers.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] "The Motown sound" played an important role in the crossover appeal with popular music, since it was the first African American–owned record label to primarily feature African-American artists.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Gordy moved Motown to Los Angeles in 1972 to pursue film production, but the company has since returned to Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Aretha Franklin, another Detroit R&B star, carried the Motown sound; however, she did not record with Berry's Motown label.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Local artists and bands rose to prominence in the 1960s and 70s, including the MC5, Glenn Frey, the Stooges, Bob Seger, Amboy Dukes featuring Ted Nugent, Mitch Ryder and The Detroit Wheels, Rare Earth, Alice Cooper, and Suzi Quatro.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The group Kiss emphasized the city's connection with rock in the song "Detroit Rock City" and the movie produced in 1999.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In the 1980s, Detroit was an important center of the hardcore punk rock underground with many nationally known bands coming out of the city and its suburbs, such as the Necros, the Meatmen, and Negative Approach.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The band Sponge toured and produced music.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city also has an active garage rock scene that has generated national attention with acts such as the White Stripes, the Von Bondies, the Detroit Cobras, the Dirtbombs, Electric Six, and the Hard Lessons.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit is cited as the birthplace of techno music in the early 1980s.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city also lends its name to an early and pioneering genre of electronic dance music, "Detroit techno".
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Featuring science fiction imagery and robotic themes, its futuristic style was greatly influenced by the geography of Detroit's urban decline and its industrial past.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Prominent Detroit techno artists include Juan Atkins, Derrick May, Kevin Saunderson, and Jeff Mills.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Detroit Electronic Music Festival, now known as Movement, occurs annually in late May on Memorial Day Weekend, and takes place in Hart Plaza.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Nederlander Organization, the largest controller of Broadway productions in New York City, originated with the purchase of the Detroit Opera House in 1922 by the Nederlander family.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Motown Motion Picture Studios with 535,000 square feet (49,700 m2) produces movies in Detroit and the surrounding area based at the Pontiac Centerpoint Business Campus for a film industry expected to employ over 4,000 people in the metro area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit is home to the world's first destination marketing organization, the Detroit Metro Convention and Visitor's Bureau, also known as Visit Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Founded in 1896, the organization now operates at 211 West Fort Street as Visit Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Because of its unique culture, distinctive architecture, and revitalization and urban renewal efforts in the 21st century, Detroit has enjoyed increased prominence as a tourist destination in recent years.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] *The New York Times* listed Detroit as the ninth-best destination in its list of *52 Places to Go in 2017*, while travel guide publisher *Lonely Planet* named Detroit the second-best city in the world to visit in 2018.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] *Time* named Detroit as one of the 50 World's Greatest Places of 2022 to explore.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Many of the area's prominent museums are in the historic cultural center neighborhood around Wayne State University and the College for Creative Studies.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] These museums include the Detroit Institute of Arts, the Detroit Historical Museum, Charles H.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Wright Museum of African American History, the Detroit Science Center, as well as the main branch of the Detroit Public Library.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] N'Namdi Gallery opened in a 16,000-square-foot (1,500 m2) complex in Midtown.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Important history of America and the Detroit area are exhibited at The Henry Ford in Dearborn, the United States' largest indoor-outdoor museum complex.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Detroit Historical Society provides information about tours of area churches, skyscrapers, and mansions.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Inside Detroit hosts tours, educational programming, and a downtown welcome center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Other sites of interest are the Detroit Zoo in Royal Oak, the Cranbrook Art Museum in Bloomfield Hills, the Anna Scripps Whitcomb Conservatory on Belle Isle, and Walter P.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Greektown and three downtown casino resort hotels serve as part of an entertainment hub.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Eastern Market farmer's distribution center is the largest open-air flowerbed market in the United States and has more than 150 foods and specialty businesses.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] On Saturdays, about 45,000 people shop there.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The annual Detroit Festival of the Arts in Midtown draws about 350,000 people.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Annual summer events include the Electronic Music Festival, International Jazz Festival, the Woodward Dream Cruise, the African World Festival, the country music Hoedown, Noel Night, and Dally in the Alley.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Within downtown, Campus Martius Park hosts large events, including the annual Motown Winter Blast.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] As the world's traditional automotive center, the city hosts the North American International Auto Show.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Held since 1924, America's Thanksgiving Parade is one of the nation's largest.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] River Days, a five-day summer festival on the International Riverfront lead up to the Windsor–Detroit International Freedom Festival fireworks, which draw super sized-crowds ranging from hundreds of thousands to over three million people.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit is one of four U.S. cities that have venues within the city representing the four major sports in North America.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit is the only city to have its four major sports teams play within its downtown district.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit is also the only city that has a team in all "Big Four" leagues, but lacks an MLS team.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Venues include: Comerica Park (home of Major League Baseball's Detroit Tigers), Ford Field (home of the National Football League's Detroit Lions), and Little Caesars Arena (home of the National Hockey League's Detroit Red Wings and the National Basketball Association's Detroit Pistons).
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit has won titles in all four of the major professional sports leagues.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Founded in 2012 as a semi-professional soccer club, Detroit City FC now plays professional soccer in the USL Championship.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Nicknamed, *Le Rouge*, the club are two-time champions of NISA since joining in 2020.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] They play their home matches in Keyworth Stadium, which is located in the enclave of Hamtramck.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In college sports, Detroit's central location within the Mid-American Conference (MAC) has made it a frequent site for the league's championship events.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] While the MAC Basketball Tournament moved permanently to Cleveland starting in 2000, the MAC Football Championship Game has been played at Ford Field since 2004 and annually attracts 25,000 to 30,000 fans.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The University of Detroit Mercy has an NCAA Division I program, and Wayne State University has both NCAA Division I and II programs.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The NCAA football GameAbove Sports Bowl (formerly, Quick Lane Bowl) is held at Ford Field each December.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city hosted the 2005 MLB All-Star Game, Super Bowl XL in 2006, the 2006 and 2012 World Series, WrestleMania 23 in 2007, and the NCAA Final Four in April 2009.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Detroit Indy Grand Prix is held in Belle Isle Park.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2007, open-wheel racing returned to Belle Isle with both Indy Racing League and American Le Mans Series Racing.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] From 1982 to 1988, Detroit held the Detroit Grand Prix, at the Detroit street circuit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Several notable athletes came from Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 1932, Eddie "The Midnight Express" Tolan from Detroit won the 100- and 200-meter races and two gold medals at the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] He was the first black athlete to win two Olympic gold medals.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Joe Louis won the heavyweight championship of the world in 1937.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit has made the most bids to host the Summer Olympics without ever being awarded the right to host the games, with seven unsuccessful bids submitted.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit bid for the 1944, 1952, 1956, 1960, 1964, 1968, and 1972 Summer Olympics, losing to London, Helsinki, Melbourne, Rome, Tokyo, Mexico City and Munich respectively.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Over 775,000 people were present in downtown Detroit over the course of the three-day event, making it the highest attended draft on record.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city is governed pursuant to the home rule *Charter of the City of Detroit*.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The government is run by a mayor, the nine-member Detroit City Council, the eleven-member Board of Police Commissioners, and a clerk.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] All of these officers are elected on a nonpartisan ballot, with the exception of four of the police commissioners, who are appointed by the mayor.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit has a "strong mayoral" system, with the mayor approving departmental appointments.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The council approves budgets, but the mayor is not obligated to adhere to any earmarking.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city clerk supervises elections and is formally charged with the maintenance of municipal records.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] City ordinances and substantially large contracts must be approved by the council.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The *Detroit City Code* is the codification of Detroit's local ordinances.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Presently three Community Advisory Councils advise City Council representatives.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Residents of each of Detroit's seven districts have the option of electing Community Advisory Councils.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Municipal elections for mayor, city council and city clerk are held at four-year intervals, in the year after presidential elections.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Following a November 2009 referendum, seven council members will be elected from districts beginning in 2013 while two will continue to be elected at-large.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit's courts are state-administered and elections are nonpartisan.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Probate Court for Wayne County is in the Coleman A.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Circuit Court is across Gratiot Avenue in the Frank Murphy Hall of Justice.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city is home to the Thirty-Sixth District Court, as well as the First District of the Michigan Court of Appeals and the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Michigan.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city provides law enforcement through the Detroit Police Department and emergency services through the Detroit Fire Department.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Beginning with its incorporation in 1802, Detroit has had a total of 74 mayors.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit's last mayor from the Republican Party was Louis Miriani, who served from 1957 to 1962.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 1973, the city elected its first black mayor, Coleman Young.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Despite development efforts, his combative style during his five terms in office was not well received by many suburban residents.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Mayor Dennis Archer, a former Michigan Supreme Court Justice, refocused the city's attention on redevelopment with a plan to permit three casinos downtown.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] By 2008, three major casino resort hotels established operations in the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2000, the city requested an investigation by the United States Justice Department into the Detroit Police Department which was concluded in 2003 over allegations regarding its use of force and civil rights violations.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city proceeded with a major reorganization of the Detroit Police Department.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2013, felony bribery charges were brought against seven building inspectors.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2016, further corruption charges were brought against 12 principals, a former school superintendent and supply vendor for a $12 million (~$15.3 million in 2024) kickback scheme.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] However, law professor Peter Henning argues Detroit's corruption is not unusual for a city its size, especially when compared with Chicago.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2025, the city elected its first woman as mayor, Mary Sheffield.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit is sometimes referred to as a sanctuary city because it has "anti-profiling ordinances that generally prohibit local police from asking about the immigration status of people who are not suspected of any crime".
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The city in recent years has been a stronghold for the Democratic Party, with around 90% of votes in the city going to incumbent vice president, Kamala Harris, the Democratic candidate in the 2024 Presidential election.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] As of 2016 many K-12 students in Detroit frequently change schools, with some children having been enrolled in seven schools before finishing their K-12 careers.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] As of 2016 because of the lack of public transportation and the lack of school bus services, many Detroit families have to rely on themselves to transport children to school.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] With about 66,000 public school students (2011–12), the Detroit Public Schools (DPS) district is the largest school district in Michigan.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit has an additional 56,000 charter school students for a combined enrollment of about 122,000 students.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] As of 2009 there are about as many students in charter schools as there are in district schools.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] As of 2016 DPS continues to have the majority of the special education pupils.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In addition, some Detroit students, as of 2016, attend public schools in other municipalities.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] With growing charter schools enrollment as well as a continued exodus of population, the city planned to close many public schools.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] State officials report a 68% graduation rate for Detroit's public schools adjusted for those who change schools.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Traditional public and charter school students in the city have performed poorly on standardized tests. c.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] 2009 and 2011, while Detroit traditional public schools scored a record low on national tests, the publicly funded charter schools did even worse than the traditional public schools.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] As of 2016 there were 30,000 excess openings in Detroit traditional public and charter schools, bearing in mind the number of K-12-aged children in the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In 2016, Kate Zernike of *The New York Times* stated school performance did not improve despite the proliferation of charters, describing the situation as "lots of choice, with no good choice".
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit public schools students scored the lowest on tests of reading and writing of all major cities in the United States in 2015.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Among eighth-graders, only 27% showed basic proficiency in math and 44% in reading.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Nearly half of Detroit's adults are functionally illiterate.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit is served by various private schools, as well as parochial Roman Catholic schools operated by the Archdiocese of Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] As of 2013 there are four Catholic grade schools and three Catholic high schools in the City of Detroit, with all of them in the city's west side.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The Archdiocese of Detroit lists a number of primary and secondary schools in the metro area as Catholic education has emigrated to the suburbs.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Of the three Catholic high schools, two are operated by the Society of Jesus and the third is co-sponsored by the Sisters, Servants of the Immaculate Heart of Mary and the Congregation of St.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit is home to several institutions of higher learning, including Wayne State University and the University of Detroit Mercy.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Grand Valley State University's Detroit Center hosts workshops, seminars, professional development, and other large gatherings.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Sacred Heart Major Seminary, founded in 1919, is affiliated with Pontifical University of Saint Thomas Aquinas, *Angelicum* in Rome and offers pontifical degrees as well as civil undergraduate and graduate degrees.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Other institutions in the city include the College for Creative Studies and Wayne County Community College.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In June 2009, the Michigan State University College of Osteopathic Medicine which is based in East Lansing opened a satellite campus at the Detroit Medical Center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit has many vocational training institutes that provide technical training to prepare students for careers in the skilled trades.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The *Detroit Free Press* and *The Detroit News* are the major daily newspapers in the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] From 1989 until their agreement expired in December 2025, both broadsheet publications were managed by a joint venture called the Detroit Media Partnership, with the *Free Press* under the ownership of USA Today Co.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] (formerly Gannett) and the *News* under MediaNews Group.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In March 2009, both newspapers reduced home delivery to three days per week, printed reduced newsstand issues on non-delivery days, and began focusing resources on Internet-based news delivery.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] In January 2026, *USA Today* acquired the *News* with plans to continue operating each newspaper separately.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] The *Metro Times*, founded in 1980, is a weekly publication covering news, arts, and entertainment.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Founded in 1935 and based in Detroit, the *Michigan Chronicle* is one of the oldest and most respected African-American weekly newspapers in America, covering politics, entertainment, sports, and community events.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Media philanthropy includes the *Detroit Free Press* high school journalism program, the Old Newsboys' Goodfellow Fund of Detroit, and the Community Foundation for Southeast Michigan's Detroit Journalism Engagement Fund.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit's television market is the 11th largest in the United States, according to estimates that do not include audiences in large areas of Ontario (including Windsor and Ottawa) who receive and watch Detroit television stations.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Detroit also has the 11th largest radio market in the United States, though this ranking also does not take into account Canadian audiences.
[src:detroit/detroit-p02] Nearby Canadian stations such as Windsor's CKLW (whose jingles formerly proclaimed "CKLW - the Motor City") are popular in Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] There are over a dozen major hospitals, which include the Detroit Medical Center (DMC), Henry Ford Health System, St.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] DMC has more than 2,000 licensed beds and 3,000 affiliated physicians.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] It is the largest private employer in the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The center is staffed by physicians from the Wayne State University School of Medicine, the largest single-campus medical school in the United States and the fourth largest medical school overall.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] DMC formally became a part of Vanguard Health Systems on December 30, 2010, as a for-profit corporation.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Vanguard has agreed to invest nearly $1.5 B in the DMC complex.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Vanguard has agreed to assume all debts and pension obligations.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] In 2011, DMC and Henry Ford Health System substantially increased investments in medical research facilities and hospitals in the city's Midtown and New Center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] In 2012, two major construction projects were begun in New Center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] As many as 500 researchers and staff will work out of the IBio Center.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] With its proximity to Canada and its facilities, ports, major highways, rail connections and international airports, Detroit is an important transportation hub.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Detroit has five border crossings: the Gordie Howe International Bridge scheduled to open in 2026, the Ambassador Bridge and the Detroit–Windsor tunnel provide motor vehicle thoroughfares, with the Michigan Central Railway Tunnel providing railroad access to and from Canada.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The fifth border crossing is the Detroit–Windsor Truck Ferry, near the Windsor Salt Mine and Zug Island.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] In 2015 Canadian Transport Minister Lisa Raitt announced Canada agreed to pay the entire cost to build a $250 million U.S.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Customs plaza adjacent to the planned new Detroit–Windsor bridge, now the Gordie Howe International Bridge.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Canada had already planned to pay for 95% of the bridge, which will cost $2.1 billion and is expected to open in early 2026.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] "This allows Canada and Michigan to move the project forward immediately to its next steps which include further design work and property acquisition on the U.S. side of the border", Raitt said issued after she spoke in the House of Commons.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Mass transit in the region is provided by bus services.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The Detroit Department of Transportation provides service within city limits up to the outer edges of the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] From there, the Suburban Mobility Authority for Regional Transportation (SMART) provides service to the suburbs and the city regionally with local routes and SMART's FAST service.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] FAST is a new service provided by SMART which offers limited stops along major corridors throughout the Detroit metropolitan area connecting the suburbs to downtown.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The new high-frequency service travels along three of Detroit's busiest corridors, Gratiot, Woodward, and Michigan, and only stops at designated FAST stops.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Cross border service between the downtown areas of Windsor and Detroit is provided by Transit Windsor via the Tunnel Bus.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Intercity bus service is offered at the Detroit Bus Station.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Greyhound Lines, Flixbus, Indian Trails, and Barons Bus Lines connect Detroit with numerous cities across the Midwest.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] An elevated rail system known as the People Mover, completed in 1987, provides daily service around a 2.94-mile (4.73 km) loop downtown.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The QLine serves as a link between the People Mover and the Amtrak station via Woodward Avenue.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The Regional Transit Authority (RTA) was established by an act of the Michigan legislature in 2012 to oversee and coordinate all existing regional mass transit operations, and to develop new transit services in the region.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The RTA's first project was the introduction of RelfeX, a limited-stop, cross-county bus service connecting downtown and midtown Detroit with Oakland county via Woodward avenue.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Amtrak provides service to Detroit, operating its *Wolverine* service between Chicago and Pontiac.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The Amtrak station is in New Center north of downtown.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The Ann Arbor–Detroit Regional Rail line will extend from New Center, connecting to Ann Arbor via Dearborn, Wayne, and Ypsilanti when it is opened.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Freight railroad operations in the city of Detroit are provided by Canadian National Railway, Canadian Pacific Railway, Conrail Shared Assets, CSX Transportation and Norfolk Southern Railway, each of which have local yards within the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Detroit is also served by the Delray Connecting Railroad and Detroit Connecting Railroad shortlines.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Detroit Metropolitan Wayne County Airport (DTW), the principal airport serving Detroit, is in nearby Romulus.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] DTW is a primary hub for Delta Air Lines (following its acquisition of Northwest Airlines), and a secondary hub for Spirit Airlines.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The airport is connected to Downtown Detroit by the Suburban Mobility Authority for Regional Transportation (SMART) FAST Michigan route.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Young International Airport (DET), previously called Detroit City Airport, is on Detroit's northeast side; the airport now maintains only charter service and general aviation.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Willow Run Airport, in western Wayne County near Ypsilanti, is a general aviation and cargo airport.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Three road systems cross the city: the original French template, with avenues radiating from the waterfront, and true north–south roads based on the Northwest Ordinance township system.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Detroit is the only major city along the Canada–U.S. border in which one travels south to cross into Canada.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Metro Detroit has an extensive toll-free network of freeways administered by the Michigan Department of Transportation.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Four major Interstate Highways surround the city.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Detroit is connected via I-75 and I-96 to Kings Highway 401 and to major Southern Ontario cities such as London, Ontario and the Greater Toronto Area.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] I-75 (Chrysler and Fisher freeways) is the region's main north–south route, serving Flint, Pontiac, Troy, and Detroit, before continuing south (as the Detroit–Toledo and Seaway Freeways) to serve many of the communities along the shore of Lake Erie.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] I-94 (Edsel Ford Freeway) runs east–west through Detroit and serves Ann Arbor to the west (where it continues to Chicago) and Port Huron to the northeast.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The stretch of the I-94 freeway from Ypsilanti to Detroit was one of America's earlier limited-access highways.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Henry Ford built it to link the factories at Willow Run and Dearborn during World War II.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] A portion was known as the Willow Run Expressway.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The I-96 freeway runs northwest–southeast through Livingston, Oakland and Wayne counties and (as the Jeffries Freeway through Wayne County) has its eastern terminus in downtown Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] I-275 runs north–south from I-75 in the south to the junction of I-96 and I-696 in the north, providing a bypass through the western suburbs of Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] I-375 is a short spur route in downtown Detroit, an extension of the Chrysler Freeway.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] I-696 (Reuther Freeway) runs east–west from the junction of I-96 and I-275, providing a route through the northern suburbs of Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Taken together, I-275 and I-696 form a semicircle around Detroit.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Michigan state highways designated with the letter M serve to connect major freeways.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Detroit has a floating post office, the *J.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Westcott II*, which serves lake freighters along the Detroit River.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] The ZIP Code is used exclusively for the *J.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Westcott II*, which makes it the only floating ZIP Code in the United States.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] It has a land-based office at 12 24th Street, just south of the Ambassador Bridge.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Westcott Company was established in 1874 by Captain John Ward Westcott as a maritime reporting agency to inform other vessels about port conditions, and the *J.
[src:detroit/detroit-p03] Westcott II* vessel began service in 1949 and is still in operation today.
